<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>How much you enjoy your food at a restaurant depends on the venue's noise, a study reveals.</p>

<p>Acoustic experts at Flinders University investigated a patron's experience under different background noise types and levels.</p>

<p>Relaxing music at 30 decibels increased the liking of food by 60 percent, but playing it at 40 decibels decreased it to 38 percent.</p>

<p>The team also found sounds from road traffic and the restaurant made customers lose their appetite at all noise levels.</p>

<p>With outdoor dining in place for much of the US due to the coronavirus pandemic, many customers sitting near a noisy street may not be enjoying their meals at all. </p>

